SIMPLE: ferrocyanide
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ferrocyanide
<hw>Fer`ro*cy"a*nide</hw> <pr>(? ⟦or⟧ ?; 104)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[<ets>Ferro-</ets> + <ets>cyanide</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>
<def>One of a series of complex double cyanides of ferrous iron and some
other base.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Potassium ferrocyanide</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>,
<cd>yellow prussiate of potash; a tough, yellow, crystalline salt,
<chform>K4(CN)6Fe</chform>, the starting point in the manufacture of
almost all cyanogen compounds, and the basis of the ferric ferrocyanate,
<xex>prussian blue</xex>. It is obtained by strongly heating together
potash, scrap iron, and animal matter containing nitrogen, as horn,
leather, blood, etc., in iron pots.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ferroprussiate</ent>⟦br⟧
